Cheap, fast, tasty.  I've been to Ken Kee several times over the past few years and what keeps us coming back is the overall cleanliness and decent quality food for prices that won't break the bank. From the variety of noodles, veggies, soups and entrees to choose from, just about everything is delicious! MSG ya say? Probably / most likely. But note they do a good job of keeping the tea and water filled.  They also have quite the selection of tea, smoothies, and boba as I've noticed. Anyways, I wouldn't say it's a go to option every time or one of my top recommended spots in Chinatown, but it's a nice change up every now and then. Only thing I would not recommend here is the salt and pepper tofu. Our order came out pretty soggy and unappetizing to eat. Other than that, no other complaints.  'Til next time!

We love the pork chops and rice, fried calamari, beef and veggies, beef brisket noodle soup, Ken Kee Fried Rice, and so many other dishes. Each item is cooked to perfection; never too mushy, too hard, or overly seasoned; always Fresh! We definitely look forward to visiting again. I'd definitely recommend Ken Kee to any one that adores clean tasting food and want to enjoy a day out with the family.

UPDATE: I am officially addicted to this place and have been back several more times since my original review! 🤗  Found this place on a late evening walk through Chinatown Square. It was extremely busy at 11pm with a very diverse clientele, so I was compelled to try it. I was not disappointed at all. The interior was bright and clean. They did not have a large staff for the amount of patrons in the restaurant, but service didn't suffer at all (we were in no rush). We enjoyed water and tea while we checked out the huge menu (great vegetarian options). Looking around the restaurant, everyone's food looked delicious with large portions, and ours was no exception. I loved the Curry Noodles w/Veggies, and am regretting not bringing an order home. Kid-friendly! My picky eater enjoyed the steamed rice and the staff was extremely accommodating and patient (reheating it up to his desired temperature) They also validate parking for the $2 lot just across from the square and library. Plus!

One of our go-to restaurants in Chinatown. Always fresh, always good. Service has always been very efficient and very good, if not always as friendly as Western reviewers like. Stopped in before the White Sox game yesterday and had a great meal. Fish soup with cilantro and preserved egg is a multi-flavored and filling soup. Ox tongue with peapods and mushrooms was great, tasty tongue meat with flavorful and chewy king mushrooms sliced thin longwise. Calamari hong kong style was the freshest fried squid I've ever had in Chicago, perfectly cooked. We've been going here for five years, and will keep coming back.

I suggest you order familiar dishes like fried rice, then go experiment with the menu. Waiter was quick and helpful with what to choose. I had a great experience personally but another friends meal didn't sit well in his stomach.

We celebrated our 2016 Chinese New Year there with a large group. The chef had set a prefix menu for us with some specialty items. So a lot of what we ate are not available on the menu. However, even the menu items are well crafted. If you can, call ahead and request the squab which is absolutely delicious.
Best sweet n sour chicken on Earth.
It was ok
Peking duck is very good
Not bad, but not that good as recommended by friends.
(Translated by Google) so so  (Original) 一般般吧

Grub Hub delivered fresh shrimp fried rice and crab rangoon.  This was the best Chinese food I've had in my life, And not by a little. Maybe the bar is just higher in Chicago, since it's the first Chinese food I've had since moving here. But it's better than anything I've had in 5 other states.

Been coming for years(decades). Food's fantastic even late night stops. Hot pots (assorted mushroom), salt/pepper fried foods (smelt& shrimp), ginger/scallions lo mien, Japanese tofu dishes (enoki or pea pod tips) just to name a few starters. Fresh and refreshing.  Small place, rare to see empty tables but wait is reasonable.  Accommodates the newbies with pictures.  End with Bubble tea or grass jelly drinks!
Nothing remarkable about the food here in comparison to many in Chinatown.
Excellent food!

I've been coming to this place for years and the food has always been great!  The food comes up super quick and everyone I've taken here wants to come back.  I love the salt and pepper calamari and the on-choy with Malaysian shrimp sauce.

Not my favorite place in Chinatown. It has a very clean look inside. Some might feel it doesn't feel traditional but this is the look you would find in Asia in a major city. Flashy and minimal.  Service was okay. I was not treated like they wanted me there. Sometimes places can come off as territorial if you're not from around here.  The food was good but not great.  There are a ton of options around when it comes to food, so be adventuresome.
Bad service and not so great food.  Waited forever for my food while both tables on my side got served and finished eating.  Was a ridiculous waiting time and not worth it at all.  Horrible service!

I had a terrible first time experience. My friend and I wanted to try this place out since it looked appealing. However, once we got inside we were treated like outsiders. The waiter basically tossed our menus at us and didn't even greet us. As time went on we kept having someone different to come by and serve us. Then finally when we got our food the waiter spilled some of our soup on the menus which they didn’t even collect. I expected better service than this; I would not recommend anyone eating there.
I love eating at this restaurant because it had a great environment and the food was served very quickly to the customer.

So this is your typical boxed Chinese restaurant. They serve similar food to Joy Yee's and Chi Cafe. I would say that the only thing that it has going for it over other places is that they are pretty quick about their service. The food is what it is. It's cheap, and it's Chinese food. You could probably order a couple of entrees and it won't break the bank like other places in Chicago. You could do a lot worse than Ken Kee.

Ken Kee is one of my favorite new places to eat at in Chinatown! Sure, there are  probably cheaper options out there, but the food was oh so delicious!!  My mom and brother were in town and wanted to grab a light dinner so we decided to try out Ken Kee - it did not disappoint! The place was pretty packed when we arrived, but luckily we came right when a table was finished.  Here's what we got:  FRIED PORK CHOPS This is one of those dishes that's pretty standard in Chinatown, but Ken Kee's were some of the best I've had. They were hot, juicy and so good! The spiciness from the chili peppers gave it an extra kick.  SALT AND PEPPER SMELT I don't know why it took me so long to discover this dish!! It's probably because I'm so desensitized from heads and tails, but boy am I glad we ordered this dish! They were hot and salty -- almost like eating french fries, but so much better! Definitely a MUST!  BABY CLAMS IN BLACK BEAN SAUCE I LOVE Ken Kee's clam dish. Hands down some of the best I've ever had in Chinatown. You gotta get it. The sauce was hearty, rich and the clams were plump and tasted super fresh compared to other places. Can't wait to get this again. NOM.  The portions are pretty generous and we had leftovers to take home. I'll definitely be back!

DISGUSTING! My girlfriend and I came to Chinatown specifically to eat at CHI TOWN CAFE, which is an awesome place to eat. UNFORTUNATELY, it was closed due to some kitchen upgrade and we were so hungry we decided to try a new Chinese restaurant.  We randomly chose this restaurant.  The tea was good, our appetizers were pretty good (CRAB RANGOON) although the service was bad, our server pretty much ignored us the whole time, which, i just shrugged off thinking it was a Chinese tradition, to kinda just back off the customer and only attend to him, when i made eye contact and signal him.  not a big deal, im not a huge fan of annoying servers, chatting you up for a tip anyway.  we shared the orange chicken entree, as well as the mixed (chicken, pork) fried rice.  the orange chicken, wasnt THAT great, but did have an authentic taste too it.  the rice was good, i liked the pieces of pork in it, so i found myself, digging through the rice to pick out all the pork meat pieces.  after i finally made eye contact with the waiter, i was able to waive him down and pay.  WE HAD LEFTOVERS, so when we asked for a box, he took to the plates to the back and boxed and bagged it for us.  when my girlfriend was eating the leftover rice, she found a HUGE THICK BLACK CURLY HAIR, the length of my index finger! it looked like an armpit hair!  i know for a FACT, that , that hair was NOT in the rice before i asked for a few boxes.  Im 100% sure, he put that hair on purpose!, either me and or my gf would of noticed that long huge hair if it was there on the plate the whole time, we pretty much, inspected the whole plate of rice, as we were eating it.  THIS PLACE IS DIRTY ! DO NOT EAT HERE!
this place wreaks of garbage go to other restraunts around it that are better,this place is for scrubs,but if u want to eat real authentic chinese food try shui wah restraunt
